result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: From Atty LaFond sent JOC in ppe provided

Defendant Cydney A. Brasch in court with attorney Britteny Mae LaFond. 
John P. Snider appeared for the State of Wisconsin. 
Plea Questionnaire / Waiver of Rights filed with the Court. 
Defendant advised of rights, waives rights and enters guilty plea to case 15CM266. 
Per DA Snider, State has completed witness responsibilities. 
Court accepts plea and finds defendant guilty regarding case 15CM266. 
Case 15CM265 is dismissed and read-in. 
Court orders sentence withheld, probation 1 year. 
Conditions: 
- pay costs, including DOMAB 
- pay supervision fees 
- submit to assessments/counseling and abide by recommendations 
- possess prescription medications only by valid prescription, and take in the manner and method as prescribed by a physician 
- report new/changing prescriptions within 72 hours 
Defendant provided with notice of appeal rights. 
Court has no objection to defendant's probation being transferred to Outagamie County.
